07290nam a22007215i 9780228010203DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280102037 a10.1515/97802280102032doi  a(DE-B1597)657232  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDS146.E85bR45 2022 7aHIS0430002bisacsh04a305.892/40422300aReligion, Ethnonationalism, and Antisemitism in the Era of the Two World Wars /ced. by Kevin P. Spicer, Rebecca Carter-Chand. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b13 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tTheorizing Religion, Ethnonationalism, and Antisemitism -- tAdopting the Swastika: George E. Deatherage and the American Nationalist Confederation, 1937–1942 -- tTransnational Antisemitic Networks and Political Christianity: The Catholic Participation in The Protocols of the Elders of Zion -- tJulius Evola and the “Jewish Problem” in Axis Europe: Race, Religion, and Antisemitism -- tSupporting Ethnonationalist Efforts -- tGerman Catholicism’s Lost Opportunity to Confront Antisemitism before the Machtergreifung -- tThe Fate of John’s Gospel during the Third Reich -- tNationalism and Religious Bonds: Transatlantic Religious Communities in Nazi Germany and the United States -- t“Often you end up asking yourself, could there be a great secret group of Jews behind it all.” – Antisemitism in the Finnish Lutheran Church after the First World War -- t“The Converts Were Just Delighted”: Dynamics of Religious Conversion as a Tool of Genocide in the Independent State of Croatia -- tCritiquing Ethnonationalism and Antisemitism -- tLearning as a Space of Protection: The Hochschule für die Wissenschaft des Judentums in Nazi Berlin -- tEthnonationalism as a Theological Crisis: Metropolitan Andrey Sheptytsky and the Greek Catholic Church in Western Ukraine, 1923–1944 -- tTo Murder or Save Thy Neighbour? Romanian Orthodox Clergymen and Jews during the Holocaust (1941–1945) -- tRacist, Brutal, and Ethnotheist: A Conservative Christian View of Nazism in the Korntal Brethren -- tEcumenical Protestant Responses to the Rise of Nazism, Fascism, and Antisemitism During the 1920s and 1930s -- tAfterword -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the wake of the devastating First World War, leaders of the victorious powers reconfigured the European continent, resulting in new understandings of nation, state, and citizenship. Religious identity, symbols, and practice became tools for politicians and church leaders alike to appropriate as instruments to define national belonging, often to the detriment of those outside the faith tradition.Religion, Ethnonationalism, and Antisemitism in the Era of the Two World Wars places the interaction between religion and ethnonationalism – a particular articulation of nationalism based upon an imagined ethnic community – at the centre of its analysis, offering a new lens through which to analyze how nationalism, ethnicity, and race became markers of inclusion and exclusion. Those who did not embrace the same ethnonationalist vision faced ostracization and persecution, with Jews experiencing pervasive exclusion and violence as centuries of antisemitic Christian rhetoric intertwined with right-wing nationalist extremism. The thread of antisemitism as a manifestation of ethnonationalism is woven through each of the essays, along with the ways in which individuals sought to critique religious ethnonationalism and the violence it inspired.With case studies from the United States, France, Italy, Germany, Finland, Croatia, Ukraine, and Romania, Religion, Ethnonationalism, and Antisemitism in the Era of the Two World Wars thoroughly explores the confluence of religion, race, ethnicity, and antisemitism that led to the annihilative destruction of the Second World War and the Holocaust, challenging readers to identify and confront the inherent dangers of narrowly defined ideologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAntisemitismzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aEthnicityzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aReligion and politicszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aAhonen, Paavo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnett, Victoria J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergen, Doris L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiliuţă, Ionuţ, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBudz, Kateryna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter-Chand, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter-Chand, Rebecca, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGallagher, Charles R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHan, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeschel, Susannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKloes, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoehne, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatijević, Danijel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuigley, Shannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpicer, Kevin P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca